The affirmative or negative nature of hypotheticals is then investi- gated. Any proposition might with truth be called both affirmative and negative, since all affirm God's existence, and deny whatever is contrary to their affirmation (pp. 16, ty). We must therefore consider how best to classify them. Some say that in any proposition composed of two, both propositions should be affirmative, or both negative, for the com· pound to be one or the other; so that, where this requisite is wanting, the resulting proposition is neither (pp. 18, l. 31—38l. Others, that the nexus alone, affirmed or denied‚ determines the quality of these proposi· tions (p. 18, l. 39 to end; p. 19, l. 1-9).
